SoK: State of the Krawlers– Evaluating the Effectiveness of Crawling Algorithms for Web Security Measurements¶

  • By Arika Khor and Dylan Zemlin

Introduction¶

Background and motivation¶

  • Web Crawlers have existed for a long time but have lacked an in depth study on their efficiency and security
  • Many crawlers have room for optimization due to using known inefficient algorithms
  • No studies have combined all well known web crawlers to understand their strengths and weaknesses

What is a Web Crawler?¶

Web Crawlers are automated programs used to browse the internet in a “human” way

  • As implied, they “crawl” the internet by following links (and other advanced techniques)
  • Used to perform various tasks
    • Scrape data from websites
    • Create website scores for search engines
    • Scan for security vulnerabilities

Web Crawlers in Security Research¶

  • Web Crawlers are critical in security research due to their robustness
  • Crawlers can help collect many different forms of data
    • Javascript Files (i.e. known malicious packages)
    • Backend Technologies (i.e. with known vulnerabilities)
    • HTTP headers/cookies
  • They can also be used to perform large scale measurements across hundreds of websites in a short amount of time

Arachnarium¶

What is Arachnarium?¶

  • A web crawler benchmarking framework
  • Modular and dockerized for maximum deployment options
  • Measures various statistics
    • M1: Code coverage (LoCs)
    • M2: Link coverage
    • M3: Javascript coverage

Notes slide for Arachnarium Architecture¶

  • Accepts config input file specifying the tests to execute
  • Scheduler deploys web app container -> executes the crawler -> runs until maximum execution time.

Why care about these metrics?¶

  • Code Coverage
    • A higher code coverage measures unique behaviours created by the server (server-side code)
  • JavaScript Source Coverage
    • A higher javascript source coverage leads to better XSS - (Cross Site Scripting) detections
  • Link Coverage
    • Better link coverage enables a more complete view of websites which can help prevent IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference) attacks

How are the measurements calculated?¶

  • Code Coverage
    • Code coverage is obtained via tools like XDebug interface, a debugging and profiling tool for PHP apps
  • JavaScript Source Coverage
    • Extracts all script tags and calculates a SHA-512 hash
  • Link Coverage
    • Extracts anchor tags and compares with exact matches of the href attribute

What is each thing? (note slide)¶

  • Link coverage is coverage of all possible url nav paths
  • code coverage means server-side exe
  • js coverage = client side execution

IDOR Attacks¶

Note slide!¶

  • IDOR attack in this case is when a user can visit a webpage that they shouldn't be able to
  • access control vulnerability
  • Examples: direct reference to database objects and static files

XSS Attacks¶

Notes slide!¶

  • Esentially manipulate website to return malicious js scripts into host
  • Several types of XSS attacks:
  • Reflected XSS: app obtains HTTP request but request is tampered with
  • Stored XSS: App receives and stores malicious HTTP data
  • DOM XSS: Client side JS processes data from malicious source, attacker can control the value of a input field

The Experiment¶

Experiment Research¶

  • Surveyed 403 papers that use crawlers
  • Extracted algorithms, parameters, and configurations

Experiment Design¶

  • Ranked against each other using the metrics discussed previously
    • Lines of code executed
    • Unique JavaScript extracted
    • Links discovered
  • Crawlers given sets of configurations
    • Time budgets
    • Page limits
    • Retry logic

Algorithms¶

Navigation¶

  • Algorithms designed to navigate a website given links
    • BFS
    • DFS
    • Random BFS
    • Random DFS
    • JAW

Page similarity algorithms Results¶

  • Sum. represents
  • R. is the
  • See that Rnd BFS still performs the best

Similarity¶

  • Algorithms designed to test the similarity of pages
    • URL Equality
    • RTED
    • SimHash
    • URL Path Equality
    • RTED-1, RTED-2, and RTED-3

Results¶

Best Performance: Navigation¶

  • Randomized BFS (Breadth First Search) came out on top
    • Performed 8% better than its non-random counterpart
  • DFS was a close second but performed 1.1% slower than Random BFS

Best Performance: Similarity¶

  • RTED-2 performed best for the LoC metric
  • Url Path Eq & QS performed best for link discovery
  • RTED-3 performed best for javascript source coverage

Best Performance: Configurations¶

  • Configurations are a combination of algorithms suited for different tasks
  • Random BFS + RTED-3 performed the best out of the chosen configurations for code coverage
  • Random BFS + Url Path Eq performed best for link discovery
  • Random BFS + Url Path Eq performed best for javascript discovery

Metrics over time¶

  • Almost all metrics should grow at a somewhat consistent rate over time as the crawler crawls
  • If there is a lack of growth, or no growth at all, it demonstrates at a crawler using sub optimal algorithms

Metrics over time cont…¶

  • However, there is diminishing return showed by not only the previous charts bottoming out, but also the rapidly of hits rapidly declining in most cases.
  • This occurs due to a lack of non-duplicate links the crawler will eventually run into given its configuration

Conclusions¶

Key Findings¶

  • Commonly used web crawling algorithms do not always perform the best
    • As we saw, randomized bfs performed better than standard bfs
  • Randomized algorithms (such as randomized bfs) are really good at total coverage analysis
  • Web crawling algorithms should be applied based on a target metric
  • Optimized web crawling algorithms may not matter based on available system resources

Summary¶

  • There is no “best” crawling methods; trade-offs depend on the goal
  • Reproducibility is still a major challenge

References¶

Performance differences: BFS and randomized BFS¶

In [20]:
import random
import time
from collections import deque

class WebCrawler:
    def __init__(self, start_url, strategy="bfs", max_pages=1000):
        self.start_url = start_url
        self.strategy = strategy
        self.max_pages = max_pages
        self.visited = set()
        self.pages_crawled = 0

    def fetch_links(self, url):
        """Simulates fetching links from a webpage."""
        return [f"{url}/page{i}" for i in range(1, 4)]

    def crawl_bfs(self):
        queue = deque([self.start_url])
        while queue and self.pages_crawled < self.max_pages:
            url = queue.popleft()
            if url in self.visited:
                continue
            self.visited.add(url)
            self.pages_crawled += 1
            queue.extend([link for link in self.fetch_links(url) if link not in self.visited])

    def crawl_randomized_bfs(self):
        queue = [self.start_url]
        while queue and self.pages_crawled < self.max_pages:
            random.shuffle(queue)
            url = queue.pop(0)
            if url in self.visited:
                continue
            self.visited.add(url)
            self.pages_crawled += 1
            queue.extend([link for link in self.fetch_links(url) if link not in self.visited])

    def start_crawl(self):
        start_time = time.time()
        if self.strategy == "bfs":
            self.crawl_bfs()
        elif self.strategy == "random_bfs":
            self.crawl_randomized_bfs()
        else:
            raise ValueError("Unknown crawling strategy")
        end_time = time.time()
        return end_time - start_time, self.pages_crawled

# Running the experiment
start_url = "http://example.com"

bfs_crawler = WebCrawler(start_url, strategy="bfs", max_pages=100)
bfs_time, bfs_pages = bfs_crawler.start_crawl()
print(f"BFS: Time Taken = {bfs_time:.4f} sec, Pages Crawled = {bfs_pages}")

random_bfs_crawler = WebCrawler(start_url, strategy="random_bfs", max_pages=100)
random_bfs_time, random_bfs_pages = random_bfs_crawler.start_crawl()
print(f"Randomized BFS: Time Taken = {random_bfs_time:.4f} sec, Pages Crawled = {random_bfs_pages}")

BFS: Time Taken = 0.0007 sec, Pages Crawled = 100
Randomized BFS: Time Taken = 0.0081 sec, Pages Crawled = 100

Webcrawler Example using beautifulsoup4¶

# Import libraries
import re
import requests
import pandas as pd
import holoviews as hv
import networkx as nx
from holoviews import opts
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
from urllib.parse import urljoin

# Holoviews extension for graph 
hv.extension('bokeh')

def web_crawler(seed_url, max_depth=2, max_pages=2):
    visited = set()
    to_visit = [(seed_url, 0)]
    graph = nx.Graph()
    data = []

    while to_visit and len(visited) < max_pages:
        url, depth = to_visit.pop(0)
        if url in visited or depth > max_depth:
            continue
        try:
            response = requests.get(url, timeout=5)
            soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
            # Extract links
            for link in soup.find_all('a', href=True):
                absolute_url = urljoin(url, link['href'])
                if absolute_url not in visited:
                    to_visit.append((absolute_url, depth + 1))
                graph.add_edge(url, absolute_url)
                data.append({"from": url, "to": absolute_url})
            visited.add(url)
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"Error fetching {url}: {e}")
    return pd.DataFrame(data), graph

# Run the crawler
df, G = web_crawler("https://wikipedia.com")

# Display results
print("Crawled Links:")
display(df.head())

# Visualize the network graph
nodes = hv.Dataset(pd.DataFrame(G.nodes(), columns=['URL']), 'URL')
graph = hv.Graph.from_networkx(G, nx.spring_layout).opts(
    opts.Graph(width=800, height=600, directed=False, node_size=5, edge_line_width=1))
graph
